lanations, theories, and historical reconstructions, but this is the first book to trace the history of the different approaches that have been applied to the question, including genealogy, linguistics, archaeology, psychology, sociology, and genetics. Weitzman shows how this quest has been fraught since its inception with religious and political agendas, how anti-Semitism cast its long shadow over generations of learning, and how recent claims about Jewish origins have been difficult to disentangle from the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. He does not offer neatly packaged conclusions but invites readers on an intellectual adventure, shedding new light on the assumptions and biases of those seeking answers-and the challenges that have made finding answers so elusive.Spanning more than two centuries and drawing on the latest findings, The Origin of the Jews brings needed clarity and historical context to this enduring and often divisive topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aJewsxHistoriography. 0aJewsxHistory. 0aJewsxOrigin. 0aJudaism. 0aReligionxOrigin. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aCharles Darwin.  aDaniel Boyarin.  aDocumentary Hypothesis.  aFerdinand de Saussure.  aGreeks.  aHabiru.  aHebrews.  aHellenistic Age.  aHellenization.  aIsrael.  aIsraelites.  aIsraeli-Palestinian conflict.  aJewish origins.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aJulius Wellhausen.  aMoses and Monotheism.  aShaye Cohen.  aShlomo Bunimovitz.  aShlomo Sand.  aSigmund Freud.  aTel Beth Shemesh.  aThe Beginnings of Jewishness.  aThe Invention of the Jewish People.  aZvi Lederman.  aancestors.  aancestry.  aanthropology.  aanti-Semitism.  aantigenealogy.  aarchaeological excavation.  aarchaeological expedition.  aarchaeology.  aconstructivist approach.  aconversion.  